            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland&#44;</placeName> O. <date>February 6th 5611</date> AM</p>
            <p>Dear <hi rend="underline">friend</hi>.</p>

            <p rend="indent(1)">Enclosed you will find a copy of my fir<add>st</add><lb/> biblical&#8211;exegetical
                prelection. The record prelection<lb/> which I intend to let you know &#40;to send
                you&#41;<lb/> next month is of far greater interest. In this<lb/> second prelection
                I endeavoured to describe exhaust<lb/>
                <del>not only</del> the meaning of heaven not only in t<add>he</add><lb/> opinion of
                the ancient people&#44; but I also endeavo<add>ur</add><lb/> to prove by logical
                conclusions based on upon the<lb/> newest physical and astronomical observation<lb/>
                how the general d&#233;luge&#44; of which the bible<lb/> speaks&#44; <del>happen</del>
                took place.<lb/> I believe that such essays are very suitable for<lb/> publication
                and the public will like to read the<add>m</add><lb/> With <hi rend="underline"
                    >kindest regards</hi>&#44; I am <hi rend="underline">as ever</hi><lb/> your <hi
                    rend="underline">friend</hi><lb/>
                <persName role="author">Isidor Kalisch</persName><lb/> On the opposite side of the
                letter is a part<lb/> of one of <persName role="author">Kalisch&#39;s</persName>
                essays&#44; dealing with the<lb/> mechanics of astronomical phenómenons.<lb/> He
                tries&#44; <del>in a layman&#39;s way</del> to show why<lb/> the 7 days of creation
                should be translated as<lb/> 7 epochs or periods<lb/> [?]<lb/>
            </p>

            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>Biblic&#8211;exegetical prelections by <persName role="author">Isidor
                    Kalisch</persName> Rab<lb/> He says that the Hebrew language <del>is really
                    a</del> should be considered<lb/>
                <del>UR</del> &#40;first&#41; Basic language. He compares certain Hebrew words<lb/>
                with the same words of modern languages<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This essay is likely to be found in the<lb/> Occident<lb/></p> 
            <p rend="align(right)">Vol IX No 1&#8212;April
                    18<add>&#63;</add><lb/> p. 34 ff<lb/>
            </p>

        </body>
